## 3. Props Interface Pattern

### Standard Props Template

```typescript
import { type VariantProps } from 'class-variance-authority';
import { type ComponentPropsWithoutRef } from 'react';

/**
 * Props for the {{ComponentName}} component.
 *
 * @example
 * ```tsx
 * <{{ComponentName}} variant="outline" size="sm">
 *   Content
 * </{{ComponentName}}>
 * ```
 */
export interface {{ComponentName}}Props
  extends ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'{{html_element}}'>
  , VariantProps<typeof {{componentName}}Variants> {
  /** Brief description of what this prop controls */
  customProp?: string;
}
```

### Rules for Props

1. **Extend native HTML props** using `ComponentPropsWithoutRef<'element'>` --
   this gives consumers access to all native attributes (className, id, aria-*, etc.)
2. **Intersect with VariantProps** when using cva for variants
3. **Document every custom prop** with JSDoc comments
4. **Use optional props** with sensible defaults -- required props should be rare
5. **Prefer primitives** over complex objects for simple props
6. **Export the interface** so consumers can reference it

### Common Prop Patterns

```typescript
// Polymorphic "as" prop
interface BoxProps<T extends React.ElementType = 'div'> {
  as?: T;
  children?: React.ReactNode;
}

// Slot pattern (for compound components)
interface CardProps {
  children?: React.ReactNode;
  header?: React.ReactNode;
  footer?: React.ReactNode;
}

// Controlled + uncontrolled
interface InputProps {
  value?: string;                    // Controlled
  defaultValue?: string;             // Uncontrolled
  onChange?: (value: string) => void; // Callback
}

// Loading / async state
interface ButtonProps {
  isLoading?: boolean;
  loadingText?: string;
  disabled?: boolean;
}
```

